attachments.text:
♫ Download + Tracklist ♫:
<http://www.deephouseamsterdam.com/mix-161-by-kidnap-kid>

Matt Relton, aka. Kidnap Kid’s music career started strong rather early: he must have been the only university student to ever have won the iTunes ‘Best Electronic Song’ in 2012 for his release ‘Vehl’ and went on to be the only postgraduate on tour with TEED and Disclosure the following year on a national ‘Hype Envoy’ tour of the United States.

His stamp onto the electronic music scene continued last year with the release of ‘Stronger’ – a club-orientated track that stood apart from its vocal-led predecessors. It opened him up to a world of new audiences as well as gaining strong support from the tastemaker cognescenti Pete Tong and Sasha. New music coming this year continues with the same style and focus, showcasing the darker, sleeker end of his dance-floor ready output.

Extensive touring in 2015 has already included multiple weeks across America, Canada and Mexico for BPM Festival, shows in Puerto Rico as well as the infamous Holy Ship. Add that to major sets at Glastonbury and Coachella, Kidnap Kid continues this spring with a solid month of US festival and club shows, rolling into a summer packed with Ibiza and European dates. One thing is for certain; the world’s clublands will be seeing a lot more of the Sheffield producer who remains one of the UK’s most successful exports.

Today, we proudly present an exclusive mixtape from Kidnap Kid just perfect for the late summer sunshine as it gradually progresses into autumn's chill. on this hour long mix, you will come across tracks from Maceo Plex, Sandrino & Frankey, Tim Green and, of course, Kidnap kid himself.

Matt Relton, aka. Kidnap Kid’s music career started strong rather early: he must have been the only university student to ever have won the iTunes ‘Best Electronic Song’ in 2012 for his release ‘Vehl’ and went on to be the only postgraduate on tour with TEED and Disclosure the following year on a national ‘Hype Envoy’ tour of the United States.

His stamp onto the electronic music scene continued last year with the release of ‘Stronger’ – a club-orientated track that stood apart from its vocal-led predecessors. It opened him up to a world of new audiences as well as gaining strong support from the tastemaker cognescenti Pete Tong and Sasha. New music coming this year continues with the same style and focus, showcasing the darker, sleeker end of his dance-floor ready output.

Extensive touring in 2015 has already included multiple weeks across America, Canada and Mexico for BPM Festival, shows in Puerto Rico as well as the infamous Holy Ship. Add that to major sets at Glastonbury and Coachella, Kidnap Kid continues this spring with a solid month of US festival and club shows, rolling into a summer packed with Ibiza and European dates. One thing is for certain; the world’s clublands will be seeing a lot more of the Sheffield producer who remains one of the UK’s most successful exports.

Today, we proudly present an exclusive mixtape from Kidnap Kid just perfect for the late summer sunshine as it gradually progresses into autumn's chill. on this hour long mix, you will come across tracks from Maceo Plex, Sandrino & Frankey, Tim Green and, of course, Kidnap kid himself.

attachments.text:
UK producer/DJ Daktyl approaches genre definition with a reckless abandon. He's got one foot in the Aussie future sound, another in a London house aesthetic, and brings healthy dose of bassweight that renders him a totally unique dance proposition.

As HARD Summer rears up to kick off this weekend, August 1-2, Daktyl will be working the Purple tent in the early afternoon on Saturday. He's prepared us a mix, the third in a series that has already welcomed Escor Krist and CRNKN. This mix brings the perfect vibes for trekking out to Pomona and kicking up dust with every mile.

The mix's vibe is house-based, with subtle rave elements rolled in. It kicks off with energy and never lets go and eschews drops for groove. "Classy" is the word that comes to mind, but classy usually never gets down like this.

attachments.title: Pao Calderón - ¡Hola THUMP Colombia! - Mixtape #3 by ThumpCo
attachments.text:
Colombia le da la bienvenida a THUMP, y para celebrar, DJs de toda la escena nacional nos ambientaron la fiesta con 10 mixtapes, 10 fiestas que nos representan, de gente que se ha labrado su camino gracias a sus vibrantes sesiones como DJ's, o a producciones que dejan entrever el enorme talento que todavía falta por explotar en Suramérica. Desde deep house refinado hasta acid house con pintas tropicales, todo un banquete de sonidos universales para que bailen, mientras nos dan la bienvenida.

La tercera entrega de ¡Hola THUMP! viene a cargo de Pao Calderón, que nació en New Jersey pero aprendió a ser DJ en estas tierras, desde el 2005. De la mano de los DJs de Cinema, Pao inició su carrera como residente de este lugar, y noche tras noche fue ganando reconocimiento, que la llevó a sonar en varias ciudades alrededor del mundo. Luego de radicarse en Nueva York y dedicarse a tocar en diferentes clubs, bodegas y hasta fiestas under, Pao fundó su propio sello llamado Dance Thorugh Life Records, con producciones que artistas como Sasha, Hernan Cattaneo y Richie Hawtin han sabido apreciar.

Esta hora de música que nos regaló, está llena de un dinamismo progresivo, que no deja de lado cierta sensibilidad en el sonido. Un contraste buenísimo para que se relajen entre semana.

A golden scooped beak slowly emerges from the darkness. Claptone is bringing us ‘Charmer’, his first artist album.

In the last few years Claptone has become known for releasing big tracks primed for late nights and packed clubs all over the world. ‘Charmer’ however fuses his signature house sound with a more eclectic aesthetic, featuring guest appearances from Nathan Nicholson (The Boxer Rebellion), Jimi Tenor, Young Galaxy, Jay-Jay Johanson and Clap Your Hands Say Yeah amongst others.

He today shares introductory track ‘Puppet Theatre’ ft. Peter, Bjorn and John, a collaboration which offers a glimpse of the depth to be found when peeling back the layers of ‘Charmer’.

The album will drop following a packed summer touring schedule which reaches all corners of the globe and it follows the run-away success of Claptone's remix for Gregory Porter, a tune which dominates Ibiza this year and has been the biggest selling track on Beatport for months on end.


The album also features ‘Dear Life’ and ‘The Music Got Me’ as well the early singles ‘No Eyes’ and ‘Ghost’, both enormous smashes on essential Berlin house label Exploited.

Claptone will be holding album launch parties all over the planet in the coming months kicking off with a special showcase at W Amsterdam on the eve of release during Amsterdam Dance Event.
‘Charmer’ is set for release on 16/10/15 on Different Recordings (the label that launched the careers of Crystal Castles, Tiga, Crystal Fighters, Vitalic).

The anthemic vocal of Anna Lunoe roars from the opening bars, luring you into a cinematic breakdown before quickly winding up into a barrage of smudging synth stabs atop a hard hitting bass line. The sounds pay homage to 90s house on an elevated level that only Lake and Lunoe could fuse in their production – adding elements of old school, acid, house and techno for a summer heater you'll be sure to hear blazing across stages this year.
